  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 29.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Hath never forgiveness",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Not that any sinner need despair of forgiveness through the fear that he may have committed this sin; for his repentance shows that his state of mind has never been one of entire enmity, and that he has not so grieved the Holy Spirit as to have been entirely forsaken by him. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "But is in danger of eternal damnation",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The Greek words, according to the most approved reading, are ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἀλλ ἔνοχός ἐστιν αἰωνίου ἁμαρτήματος",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "but is guilty of an eternal sin",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; thus showing that there are sins of which the effects and the punishment belong to eternity. He is bound by a chain or' sin from which he can never be loosed. (See St. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 9:41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"Therefore your sin remaineth.\") Mark 3:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Guilty (ἔνοχος)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "From ἐν, in, ἔχω, to hold or have. Lit., is in the grasp of, or holden of. Compare 1 Corinthians 11:27; James 2:10.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "From ἐν, in, ἔχω, to hold or have. Lit., is in the grasp of, or holden of. Compare ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Corinthians 11:27",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "James 2:10",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Eternal damnation (αἰωνίου ἁμαρτήματος)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "An utterly false rendering. Rightly as Rev., of an eternal sin. So Wyc., everlasting trespass. The A. V. has gone wrong in following Tyndale, who, in turn, followed the erroneous text of Erasmus, κρίσεως, judgment, wrongly rendered damnation. See Matthew 23:33, and compare Rev. there. ",
        "children": [
          {
